    <!-- Page Header -->
    <header class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow p-6 border-l-4 border-l-emerald-500">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Extended Essay – Language B</h1>
      <p class="text-slate-700">
        This page gives an overview of what makes a strong Language B extended essay:
        possible approaches, structure, sources, and how the assessment criteria A–E
        apply to your work.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- What is the EE? -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow p-6 space-y-3">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">1. What is the Extended Essay?</h2>
      <p>
        The extended essay is a <strong>4,000-word research paper</strong> in which you investigate a topic of your choice.
        In Language B, it must be clearly connected to the
        <strong>language</strong> you are studying and to the <strong>culture(s)</strong> where that language is used.
      </p>
      <p>Your essay should:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 space-y-1">
        <li>Answer a <strong>clear, focused research question</strong>.</li>
        <li>Use appropriate <strong>research methods</strong> and in-depth analysis.</li>
        <li>Build a <strong>reasoned, evidence-based argument</strong>, not just a description.</li>
        <li>Follow a <strong>coherent structure</strong> (introduction, body, conclusion).</li>
        <li>Show understanding of the <strong>language</strong>, its <strong>cultural context</strong>,
            and key <strong>concepts and terminology</strong> of the subject.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-2">
        You cannot write a Language B EE in a language that you are studying as Language A, and
        the main texts you analyse must be originally written/spoken in the Language B, not translations.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- What is special about Language B -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow p-6 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">2. What is special about a Language B EE?</h2>
      <p>
        A Language B extended essay should deepen your knowledge of the target language and your
        understanding of its culture. Most essays fall into one (or a combination) of these three areas:
      </p>

      <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
        <!-- Literary analysis -->
        <article class="rounded-xl border border-emerald-100 bg-emerald-50 p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-1">a) Literary analysis</h3>
          <p class="text-sm mb-2">
            Close study of a literary work (or works) originally written in the target language.
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Theme, character, narrative voice, symbolism, etc.</li>
            <li>Comparison of two works from different periods.</li>
            <li>Screenplay or song lyrics treated as <em>literature</em> (focus on language, not camera work).</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <!-- Language use -->
        <article class="rounded-xl border border-sky-100 bg-sky-50 p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-1">b) Language use</h3>
          <p class="text-sm mb-2">
            Analysis of how the language is used, structured or developed in real contexts.
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Rhetoric in political speeches or campaigns.</li>
            <li>Varieties of slang in music, social media, or youth culture.</li>
            <li>Changes in language use in a specific community.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate-600 mt-2">
            The focus must be on the <strong>language itself</strong>, not on how people learn it.
          </p>
        </article>

        <!-- Cultural study -->
        <article class="rounded-xl border border-amber-100 bg-amber-50 p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-1">c) Cultural study</h3>
          <p class="text-sm mb-2">
            A sociocultural issue specific to the target culture, explored through:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Its effect on language (slogans, metaphors, discourse).</li>
            <li>Its representation in cultural artefacts: films, series, ads, music videos, etc.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate-600 mt-2">
            Issues that are purely “global” (for example generic emoji use) are too broad unless
            you show what is distinct in the Language B context.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Basic essay structure -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow p-6 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">3. Basic structure of your essay</h2>
      <p>This matches the structure shown in Figure 10 of the EE guide.</p>

      <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
        <!-- Intro -->
        <div class="bg-lime-50 border border-lime-200 rounded-2xl p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-1">Introduction</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Present the topic and context.</li>
            <li>Give essential background information.</li>
            <li>Explain why the topic is worth studying in Language B.</li>
            <li>End with your <strong>research question</strong>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Body -->
        <div class="bg-cyan-50 border border-cyan-200 rounded-2xl p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-1">Body</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Each paragraph develops <strong>one main point</strong>.</li>
            <li>Analyse, discuss and evaluate your research findings.</li>
            <li>Use quotations / examples in the target language.</li>
            <li>Build a clear <strong>line of argument</strong> supported by evidence.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Conclusion -->
        <div class="bg-fuchsia-50 border border-fuchsia-200 rounded-2xl p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-1">Conclusion</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Directly answer the research question.</li>
            <li>Bring your main points together (no new ideas).</li>
            <li>Explain why your findings matter for the language/culture studied.</li>
            <li>Suggest possible implications or further questions.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Sources -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow p-6 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">4. Using sources</h2>
      <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="border border-violet-100 bg-violet-50 rounded-xl p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-1">Primary sources</h3>
          <p class="text-sm mb-2">
            Original material you analyse directly.
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Novels, short stories, poems, plays, films, series, ads.</li>
            <li>Speeches, song lyrics, interviews, surveys you conduct.</li>
            <li>Historical documents, political posters, graffiti, etc.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="border border-indigo-100 bg-indigo-50 rounded-xl p-4">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-1">Secondary sources</h3>
          <p class="text-sm mb-2">
            Sources that analyse or interpret primary material.
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Literary criticism and academic articles.</li>
            <li>Books on culture, history, or media.</li>
            <li>Reliable news reports, statistics and surveys.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-700">
        Most Language B essays need a <strong>mix of primary and secondary sources</strong>.
        Keep track of everything you use and cite it correctly (our class uses
        <strong>APA style</strong>).
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Criteria A–E quick guide -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow p-6 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">5. Assessment criteria A–E (quick guide)</h2>
      <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        <article class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-slate-200">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1">Criterion A – Framework</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Clear, focused research question in Language B.</li>
            <li>Methods and approach are explained and appropriate.</li>
            <li>Essay has a logical structure that the reader can follow.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-slate-200">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1">Criterion B – Knowledge &amp; understanding</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Shows accurate understanding of texts, language and culture.</li>
            <li>Uses subject terminology correctly (eg. symbolism, register, metaphor).</li>
            <li>Engages with key concepts (identity, gender roles, marginalization, etc.).</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-slate-200">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1">Criterion C – Analysis &amp; line of argument</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Goes beyond description to explain <em>how</em> and <em>why</em>.</li>
            <li>Each point is supported by evidence from research.</li>
            <li>Clear thread from research question → findings → conclusion.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-slate-200">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1">Criterion D – Discussion &amp; evaluation</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>Discusses the significance of findings from different perspectives.</li>
            <li>Evaluates strengths and limitations of sources and methods.</li>
            <li>Weaves this evaluation into the argument instead of isolating it.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-slate-200 md:col-span-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1">Criterion E – Reflection</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>RPPF reflections show how your ideas and question developed.</li>
            <li>Explains what you learned as a researcher and language learner.</li>
            <li>Connects the EE experience to future studies or interests.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Sample questions -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow p-6 space-y-4 mb-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">6. Sample research-question styles</h2>
      <p class="text-sm">
        These are <em>models</em> of how a good question might be phrased. Your actual question
        must be your own and tailored to the texts / artefacts you choose.
      </p>
      <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-emerald-100 bg-emerald-50">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide">Language use</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-xs space-y-1">
            <li>To what extent do the inaugural speeches of two presidents differ in their use of ethos, pathos and logos?</li>
            <li>How has social-media language in &lt;country&gt; reshaped traditional forms of politeness?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-sky-100 bg-sky-50">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide">Literary analysis</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-xs space-y-1">
            <li>How does the choice of narrator influence the reader’s empathy towards the main character in &lt;novel&gt;?</li>
            <li>In what ways do two novels from different decades portray migration and identity differently?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="border rounded-xl p-4 border-amber-100 bg-amber-50">
          <h3 class="font-semibold mb-1 text-sm uppercase tracking-wide">Cultural study</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-xs space-y-1">
            <li>To what extent do Super Bowl commercials for &lt;brand&gt; promote values commonly associated with US culture?</li>
            <li>How accurately does a particular protest song reflect current debates on racism in &lt;country&gt;?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>
